<catsoop-section>Instructions</catsoop-section>

1. Use the ruler with markings 0, 1, 2, 6, 10 and 13 to measure all the distances from 1 to 13. For example, distance 1 can be measured between 0 and 1 (or between 1 and 2), distance 3 can be measured between markings 10 and 13 (13 - 10 = 3). (Ref. Fig. no.1)

2. The key property of a Golomb ruler is that no two pairs of marks have the same distance between them. Therefore, this is not an exact Golomb ruler but a variation of it. But the variation makes it possible to measure all the distances from 1 to 13 with this ruler in minimum markings. Such a type of ruler where you can measure all the distances is called a perfect ruler.

3. Use the other ruler with markings 0, 1, 4, 10, 12, 15 and 17 to measure all the distances from 1 to 17. (Ref. Fig. no. 3)


<catsoop-section>What's Happening</catsoop-section>

- How many minimum markings do you need given the length of the ruler?

- For the first ruler, you have 13 distances that have to be measured (1, 2, 3, ...13). The required number of markings (m) on the ruler can be determined by solving $^mC_2 = 13$. This gives m = 6.

- Out of these six points, the markings 0 and 13 are mandatory (in order to measure 13). The remaining four points can be determined by the trial and error approach.

- Similarly, for the second ruler, we have to solve for the equation $^mC_2 = 17$, giving m = 7. Therefore we need at least 7 markings for the second ruler.

